title: Replies to supplementary questions raised by Finance Committee Members in examining the Estimates of Expenditure 2023-24
question_text: First of all, I would like to thank the Government for allowing this year’s Consumption Voucher Scheme to cover people who have come to live in Hong Kong through different admission schemes for talent, professionals and entrepreneurs, as well as people who have come to study in Hong Kong, enabling them to receive the vouchers in half value. As reflected by the robust performance of the local retail and catering sectors during the Easter holidays, the effect of the consumption vouchers in stimulating consumer spending will become more obvious in 2023. According to a survey conducted by the Lingnan University in June 2021 on consumers’ intention to receive and use consumer vouchers, one in six respondents expressed their willingness to donate the vouchers to charities. There are however restrictions on such donations, and the use of consumption vouchers is in principle not applicable to charitable donations at present. Will the Government consider taking appropriate measures by, for example, allowing charities to give the vouchers to the grassroots (such as the unemployed or low income families) on a matching basis so that they may use the money to buy daily necessities?
reply_text: The purpose of launching 2023 Consumption Voucher Scheme is to expedite the overall recovery of the economy by stimulating local consumption at a time when the society is gradually returning to normal and the economy has become relatively stable, and to consolidate the extensive use of electronic payment in Hong Kong. Consumption vouchers can be used at local retail, catering and service outlets or their online platforms which accept payments by the six stored value facilities participating in the Scheme (i.e. AlipayHK, BoC Pay, Octopus, PayMe from HSBC, Tap & Go and WeChat Pay HK). In view of the above objective, consumption vouchers cannot be used for direct donation to charitable organisations. Nonetheless, people may use other means, such as purchasing suitable products or services with consumption vouchers, and then donate them to people in need or charitable organisations. - End - Session 5 FSTB(Tsy) - Page 6
